  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Anne W. Weston describes a difficult afternoon at school. &quot;I don&apos;t see why Garrison should think Solomon Carpenter&apos;s sending for the $1000 more out of taste than his offering it. ...H. C. Wright&apos;s letter struck me as mere talk. He cannot pass off separation from the Widow Stickney as a living martyrdom.&quot; Anne listened from her room to a conversation between Mr. Holmes and the Beanes about the (negro) pew question. Anne received Deborah&apos;s letter tonight, and she cried for as long as she wanted to. Anne attended S. Hawley&apos;s church on Sunday; and in the afternoon, read Jonathan Edwards on the affections. &quot;He lays such a stress on works as would astonish the ministers of the present generation.&quot; [The work by Jonathan Edwards was first published in 1746 under title: A treatise concerning religious affections.]</subfield>
